Author-Workplace-Name: University of Oregon 
Title: Financing Policy, Basis Risk, and Corporate Hedging: Evidence from Oil and Gas Producers 
Abstract:
 This paper studies the hedging policies of oil and gas producers between
 1992 and 1994. My evidence shows that the extent of hedging is related to
 financing costs. In particular, companies with greater financial leverage
 manage price risks more extensively.My evidence also shows that the
 likelihood of hedging is related to economies of scale in hedging costs
 and to the basis risk associated with hedging instruments. Larger
 companies and companies whose production is located primarily in regions
 where prices have a high correlation with the prices on which
 exchange-traded derivatives are based are more likely to manage risks. Copyright The American Finance Association 2000. 
