Author-Name: Benjamin S. Wilner 
Author-Workplace-Name: LECG/Navigant Consulting, Evanston, Illinois 
Title: The Exploitation of Relationships in Financial Distress: The Case of Trade Credit 
Abstract:
 This paper develops optimal pricing, lending, and renegotiation strategies
 for companies in relationships where one firm is highly dependent on the
 other. Long-term trade-creditor firm relationships induce dependent trade
 creditors to grant more concessions in debt renegotiations than
 nondependent creditors. Anticipating these larger renegotiation
 concessions, not only do less financially stable firms prefer trade
 credit, but all firms agree to pay a higher interest rate for trade
 credit. The model also explains the existence of "teaser" interest rates
 and convenience classes. Findings are consistent with those of the
 relationship-lending literature. Copyright The American Finance Association 2000. 
