Author-Name: Jonathan B. Berk 
Author-Workplace-Name: University of California, Berkeley, and NBER 
Title: Sorting Out Sorts 
Abstract:
 In this paper we analyze the theoretical implications of sorting data into
 groups and then running asset pricing tests within each group. We show
 that the way this procedure is implemented introduces a bias in favor of
 rejecting the model under consideration. By simply picking enough groups
 to sort into, the true asset pricing model can be shown to have no
 explanatory power within each group. Copyright The American Finance Association 2000. 
