Author-Name: Paul Schultz 
Author-Workplace-Name: University of Notre Dame 
Title: Stock Splits, Tick Size, and Sponsorship 
Abstract:
 A traditional explanation for stock splits is that they increase the
 number of small shareholders who own the stock. A possible reason for the
 increase is that the minimum bid-ask spread is wider after a split and
 brokers have more incentive to promote a stock. I document a large number
 of small buy orders following Nasdaq and NYSE/AMEX splits during 1993 to
 1994. I also find strong evidence that trading costs increase, and weak
 evidence that costs of market making decline following splits. This is
 consistent with splits acting as an incentive to brokers to promote
 stocks. Copyright The American Finance Association 2000. 
